GIT:
---git stands for Global Information Tracker (GIT).
---A Version Control System (VCS).
---It helps developers track changes in their code, collaborate with others, and manage different versions of a project.
---It is a software
---Works locally on your computer.


GITHUB:
---A cloud-based hosting service that stores Git repositories online.
---It allows developers to:
        -->Share code with others
        -->Collaborate on projects
        -->Contribute to open-source projects
        -->Manage issues and project workflows
---It is a website/platform to host Git repositories.


INSTALL GIT:
1.Download Git:
---Go to: https://git-scm.com/downloads
---Choose your OS (Windows, macOS, Linux).
2.Install Git
---Run the installer.
---Keep default options (recommended).
---After installation, open Command Prompt (Windows) or Terminal (Mac/Linux).
3.Verify Installation

git --version

If it shows a version (e.g., git version 2.42.0), installation is successful.

SETTING UP GIT(FIRST TIME ONLY):
Run these commands (replace with your info):

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "youremail@example.com"


CREATING A GITHUB ACCOUNT & LOGIN:
1.Go to: https://github.com
2.Click Sign up.
3.Enter details:
    -->Username
    -->Email
    -->Password
    -->Verify email
4.Once signed up, log in with your credentials

CONNECTING GIT WITH GITHUB(USING HTTPS)
Go to your GitHub → Settings → Developer settings → Personal access tokens.
Generate a token (with repo access).
When you run git push for the first time, Git will ask for:
Username → your GitHub username
Password → paste the token